sub_title: Product Design Lead at de Bijenkorf
summary:
I work and live for creating products and services that will make peopleâ€™s lives easier and happier. With background in industrial design engineering, for the past ten years I have shifted my focus towards user-centred digital experiences trying to steer to where the big winds are moving. I have worked on projects large and small, from conceptualisation to prototyping and shipping into the market. A strong believer of user-driven design, I derive my conclusions based on data while having developed a good intuition for good design. Keen on details with the big picture in mind, I bring my theoretical and practical knowledge, research, analytical and creative skills into creating efficient and delightful user experiences. 

Having lived and worked in four countries, I have acquired a global mind and multi-national experience, both of which have shaped me into a well-rounded design leader.

In my free time, I write about my thoughts and experiences on design-related topics on medium.

[{'title': 'Design of a Frugal Thermometer for Uganda', 'date': {'start': {'month': 8, 'day': None, 'year': 2013}, 'end': {'month': 2, 'day': None, 'year': 2014}}, 'description': 'A problem that was identified is that the method for fever diagnosis of mothers and children in Uganda is intuitive, subjective and inaccurate. Therefore the goal of our project is to develop a product, service or system that objectively measures fever and non-fever. 

The measurement of non-fever is especially critical as many mothers and children travel long distances to see a doctor, or buy expensive medication while they are actually not feverish. The over-use of medicine makes them resistant to antibiotics which causes bigger problems. 

This project is to design a frugal thermometer that will detect fever, as well as the cases of non-fever  to protect the people in Uganda in longer term.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Eleonora', 'last_name': 'Ibragimova', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Product Design Lead at de Bijenkorf'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Caspar', 'last_name': 'Smits', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Digital Creative at Toupim'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Alkisti', 'last_name': 'Kokorikou', 'name': None, 'headline': 'ðŸŽ¯ User Centered Designer'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Jingwen', 'last_name': 'Yao', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Freelance Digital Designer'}]}, {'title': 'Sustainable Product-Service System Strategy Design for Bottom of the Pyramid (BoP) for Africa', 'date': {'start': {'month': 1, 'day': None, 'year': 2013}, 'end': {'month': 6, 'day': None, 'year': 2013}}, 'description': 'Joint project of Royal Philips (Eindhoven, the Netherlands) and Faculty of Industrial Design Engineering, TU Delft for inspiring Philips African Project Team

The symptoms are more likely to appear when a person is overexercising himself; this makes the affliction especially destructive for overworkers - people that highly motivated to keep on working even when experiencing pain.
The aim of the project is to create concepts to allow the overworker to continue working, but in a controlled manner that can be considered healthier and more sustainable for the functioning of the overworker. This design process contains an internal analysis on Philips, an external analysis of the industry, an analysis of the user and an analysis of uncertainty in the design.
